Demonstration of Persistent Communication
-----------------------------------------

Persistent communication in MPI is a way to set up a send or receive once and
reuse it many times with the same arguments (for instance when the buffer is
the same, but it keeps changing). It is useful when the same communication
pattern repeats in a loop, because it reduces setup overhead compared with
creating a new nonblocking request every iteration.

In MPI, you first create a persistent request with an _init routine such as
MPI_Send_init or MPI_Recv_init, then start it with MPI_Start or MPI_Startall,
wait for completion with MPI_Wait, and finally free it with MPI_Request_free
when you are done. The actual message data is not stored in the request; the
request stores the communication parameters so they can be reused.

    NOTE:
        MPI_Start only initiates the persistent communication; it does not mean
        the transfer is finished. You need MPI_Wait or MPI_Test to ensure the
        operation completes before you reuse the request or touch the buffers
        again.

        The key reason is safety: after MPI_Start, the send buffer must stay
        unchanged, and the receive buffer must not be read, until completion.
        MPI_Wait marks the request inactive again, which makes it legal to
        start it another time.

Persistent communication is best for repeated point-to-point exchanges where
the source, destination, datatype, count, tag, and communicator stay the same
across iterations. It does not automatically make communication faster on the
network itself, but it can reduce repeated setup cost in the MPI library.

> a persistent communication request is *inactive* after it was created --- no
> active communication is attached to the request.

> A communication that uses a *persistent communication request* is *started*
> by the function MPI_START.
